"{\"uid\": \"today.com-news-paris-olympics-jordan-chiles-bronze-medal-controversy-rcna166095\", \"text\": \"A Michael Kors Bag, Suede Slippers and More Holiday Gifts at Walmart - Starting at $9    Becca Wood  News and Trending Reporter/Editor  Samantha Kubota  Senior Editor  Ariana Brockington  Trending News Reporter  Jordan Chiles being stripped of her bronze medal was one of the most controversial moments during the 2024 Paris Olympics.  The gymnast was first given a score of 13.666 in the Olympic floor finals on Aug. 5, which initially put her in fifth place. However, after Team USA submitted an inquiry, arguing that the judges neglected to credit Chiles for a skill, her score was increased to 13.766.  The score changepropelled the 23-year-old to third place on the podium, surpassing two Romanian gymnasts, Ana B\\u0103rbosu and Sabrina Maneca-Voinea, as a result.  Days later, following an appeal from Team Romania, the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) said Chiles' inquiry was submitted too late and that her original score would be reinstated. The decision ultimately stripped Chiles of the bronze medal.  Here's everything to know about the Jordan Chiles' medal controversy and what has happened since then.  After Chiles was awarded the bronze medal in Paris, Romanian officials filed a complaint with CAS, arguing Team USA'sinquiry on Chiles' score was submitted past the one-minute deadline.  The courtthenissued their decision that Chiles' inquiry was submitted four seconds late on Aug. 10, recommending that her original floor routine score be reinstated. The International Olympic Committee (IOC) said Aug. 11 that the organization \\\"will reallocate\\\" the bronze medal from Chiles to B\\u0103rbosu.  USA Gymnastics (USAG) filed an appeal with video evidence on Chiles' behalf shortly after, stating that Team USA had submitted the initial inquiry within 47 seconds of Chiles' score being posted, which would put the request within the one-minute deadline.  However, the CAS declined their appeal, citing rules \\\"do not allow for an arbitral award to be reconsidered even when conclusive new evidence is presented.\\\"  In astatement posted to Xon Aug. 12, USAG said it is continuing to pursue \\\"every possible avenue\\\" of an appeal on behalf of Chiles to get her bronze medal reinstated, despite the CAS declining its initial efforts.  \\\"We are deeply disappointed by the notification and will continue to pursue every possible avenue and appeal process, including to the Swiss Federal Tribunal, to ensure the just scoring, placement, and medal award for Jordan (Chiles),\\\" USAG said.  CAS said in an Aug. 12 statement toThe Athleticthat both Team USA and the Romanian federation had \\\"ample opportunities to present their arguments and objections\\\" about the U.S. challenge being made four seconds late.  However, CAS did the leave the door open for the case to be revisited.  \\\"If new evidence (i.e. objectively unknown at the time of the CAS hearing) appears after the issuance of the CAS decision, it would be possible to ask the Swiss Federal Tribunal to order that the case be reopened,\\\" CAS said in its statement. \\\"The CAS would also reopen the case spontaneously if all parties agree.\\\"  On Sept. 16, Chiles' attorneys announced that she appealed to the Federal Supreme Court of Switzerland to overturn the CAS ruling that her challenge in the women's floor exercise final in Paris was submitted four seconds too late.  Chiles' appeal claimed that the CAS' decision violated her \\\"right to be heard,\\\" among other procedural issues. Her appeal also alleges a conflict of interest regarding Hamid Gharavi, the president of the CAS arbitration panel, and his previous work as a counsel for Romania,NBC News reported.  The CAS ultimatelyruled that Team USA's scoring inquiry should be voided, which would restore the original finishing order with B\\u0103rbosu at third, Maneca-Voinea at fourth and Chiles at fifth.  Romania's appeal also asked that Maneca-Voinea's score be adjusted to add 0.1 after she was given a deduction to her score \\\"without basis.\\\" The court, however, dismissed the request.  B\\u0103rbosu received a bronze medal on Aug. 16.  Speaking to reporters after the ceremony, B\\u0103rbosu said that the controversy was \\\"saddening\\\" and that she was sending U.S. gymnasts \\\"good thoughts.\\\"  \\\"I am thinking of them even if today I got the medal,\\\" she said.  B\\u0103rbosu added that \\\"we expected the referees and staff at the Olympics to do their job properly.\\\"  On Aug. 10, Chiles shared three broken-heart emoji on her Instagram story, writing in a subsequent message that she would be \\\"taking this time and removing myself from social media\\\" for her mental health.  Several days later, on Aug. 15, Chiles issued astatement to Instagramsaying that she was \\\"overwhelmed by the love\\\" she had received and thanked everyone for their support after being stripped of her medal and the court's decision to deny the USAG appeal.  \\\"This decision feels unjust and comes as a significant blow, not just to me, but to everyone who has championed my journey,\\\" she said.  She also condemned the online attacks she had been subjected to since the ruling, adding that \\\"unprompted racially driven attacks on social media\\\" about her have been \\\"extremely hurtful.\\\"  \\\"I have poured my heart and soul into this sport and I am so proud to represent my culture and my country,\\\" she continued. \\\"I will never waver from my values of competing with integrity, striving for excellence, upholding the values of sportsmanship and the rules that dictate fairness.\\\"  On Nov. 11,Chiles gave her first live TV interviewsince thescoring controversyon TODAY, telling Hoda Kotb that she now feels \\\"comfortable\\\" to talk about her experience.  \\\"Honestly, it's been really, really hard just to comprehend everything that's been happening,\\\" Chiles said, becoming emotional. \\\"I have been able to finally now feel comfortable in a way to talk about what has been happening. \\u2026 it's just been a difficult time for myself and I am ready to speak on my truth.\\\"  She continued, \\\"I think now, it's just the support that's been around me that I have been like, 'OK, I can not control anything that's happening on the outside, I can only control what my truth is, and I know what the truth is, and I know that we were right in everything that we were doing.'\\\"  Chiles said her late grandfather's memory has given her strength over the last several months, recalling advice he'd given her: \\\"'Everything happens for a reason. There is reasons on why you are the person you are. There is reasons on why people look up to you.'\\\"  After the IOC asked that Chiles return the bronze medal on Aug. 11, the U.S. Olympic & Paralympic Committee (USOPC) said in a statement that they plan to appeal the decision.  \\\"We firmly believe that Jordan rightfully earned the bronze medal, and there were critical errors in both the initial scoring by the International Gymnastics Federation (FIG) and the subsequent CAS appeal process that need to be addressed,\\\" the statement began.  \\\"The initial error occurred in the scoring by FIG, and the second error was during the CAS appeal process, where the USOPC was not given adequate time or notice to effectively challenge the decision,\\\" the statement continued.  On Aug. 14, USOPC shared a statement that they \\\"strongly contest\\\" the CAS decision to deny their appeal due to \\\"significant procedural errors.\\\" The group claimed that crucial information was sent to the wrong email addresses for USOPC and USA Gymnastics, which deprived them from having enough time to gather evidence and properly object the CAS ruling.  In the wake of the ruling, members of the U.S. Olympic women's gymnastics team shared their support for their teammate on social media.  Biles shared a photo on her Instagram story hugging a crying Chiles, adding several heart emojis over the picture. She penned a touching message to her teammate on the post, writing, \\\"sending you so much love Jordan.\\\"  \\\"keep your chin up olympic champ!\\\" she added. \\\"we love you!\\\"  Sunisa Lee shared her own message of support for Chiles on her Instagram story, resharing the statement from USA Gymnastics.  \\\"All this talk about the athlete, what about the judges??\\\" she wrote alongside the statement. \\\"Completely unacceptable. this is awful and i am gutted for Jordan. i got your back forever Jo. u have all my flowers and you will ALWAYS be an olympic\\u00a0champion.\\\"  Jade Carey had a similar sentiment to Lee, resharing the same statement alongside the message, \\\"do not punish the athlete for someone else's mistake.\\\"  \\\"With you all the way jo,\\\" Carey added. \\\"You are forever an olympic champion that has so much to be proud of.\\\"  Hezly Rivera also posted the USA Gymnastics statement, writing on her Instagram story, \\\"love you @jordanchiles and will always support you!!!\\\"  Aly Raisman, a six-time Olympic medalist who competed with USA's women's gymnastics in Rio in 2016 and London in 2012,took to Xon Aug. 10 to comment about the event that \\\"no athlete should ever go through.\\\"  \\\"This is unfair & cruel. Athlete fairness & athlete mental health matters,\\\" Raisman penned. \\\"Athletes should not suffer from mistakes that are out of their control.\\\"  Raisman found herself in a similar situation at the 2012 Games when her coach appealed a tie-breaking, third-place score on the balance beam finals. She ended up receiving the bronze.  On Aug. 16,Raisman came on TODAYafter Chiles spoke out about her bronze medal being \\\"stripped away.\\\"  \\\"I really can not even imagine what this has been like for Jordan,\\\" Raisman expressed. \\\"I feel awful because it was such an incredible Olympic Games and to be able to watch Jordan on that podium with Rebeca and Simone is one of the most iconic moments in sports, in my opinion, and something that will live on forever.  Becca Wood is a news and trending reporter for TODAY Digital based in New York City. Follow her on Instagram and Twitter.  Sam Kubota is a senior digital editor and journalist for TODAY Digital based in Los Angeles. She joined NBC News in 2019.  Ariana Brockington is a trending news reporter at TODAY digital. She is based in Los Angeles.  \\u00a9\\u00a02025 NBCUniversal Media, LLCApple\\u00ae, Apple logo\\u00ae and App Store\\u00ae are registered trademarks of Apple Inc.\"}"